{
  "body": "The Ford Ranger's off-road capabilities and terrain adaptation features are engineered to meet the demands of diverse and challenging Australian landscapes, including rugged outback, sandy deserts, rocky tracks, and wet conditions. Key off-road features include substantial ground clearance, advanced suspension systems, robust 4x4 drivetrains, locking differentials, and underbody protection.\n\n**Ground Clearance:** The 2025 Ford Ranger models available in Australia offer ground clearance typically around 234 mm (9.3 inches) for standard variants, with the Ranger Raptor and higher-end models providing up to 10.7 inches (approximately 272 mm) of clearance. This elevated stance allows the vehicle to navigate uneven terrain, rocks, and water crossings without undercarriage damage, essential for Australian off-road conditions where terrain can be unpredictable[1][4][8].\n\n**Suspension Systems:** The Ranger employs a front independent suspension with control arms and a rear live axle setup, balancing on-road comfort with off-road durability. The suspension is tuned to absorb shocks from rough terrain, maintaining wheel contact and traction. The Ranger Raptor variant features a more specialized suspension with Fox Racing shocks and increased travel, designed for high-speed off-road driving and extreme terrain adaptability[3][8].\n\n**4x4 Drivetrain and Locking Differentials:** The Ranger's 4x4 system is selectable, allowing drivers to switch between 2WD and 4WD modes depending on terrain. It includes front and rear locking differentials, which enhance traction by ensuring power is distributed evenly to wheels with grip, crucial when traversing slippery mud, loose sand, or steep inclines common in Australian environments. The availability of multiple drive modes tailored for different off-road conditions further optimizes performance and control[4][7].\n\n**Underbody Protection:** To protect vital mechanical components, the Ranger is equipped with skid plates and reinforced underbody guards. These features prevent damage from rocks, debris, and rough ground, which are frequent hazards in Australian outback exploration. The robust chassis and frame construction also contribute to durability and resilience in harsh off-road use[4][8].\n\n**Tires and Wheels:** Off-road capable tires such as the Goodyear Wrangler Territory AT (All-Terrain) with sizes like 255/65R18 are standard or available on many Ranger variants, providing a balance of traction and durability on mixed surfaces. Wheel sizes vary from 17 to 18 inches depending on the model, supporting both off-road grip and load capacity[3][4].\n\nCollectively, these features enable the Ford Ranger to perform reliably across Australia's varied terrains, from sandy beaches and red dirt tracks to rocky escarpments and muddy trails, making it a versatile vehicle for exploration, work, and recreational off-roading in the Australian context.",
