{
  "body": "The Ford Ranger range available in Australia offers robust towing and payload capacities that significantly enhance its utility for exploration, work, and support of key Australian industries such as agriculture and mining. Standard Ranger models, such as the 2025 Ford Ranger XLT, feature a braked towing capacity of up to 3,500 kg and an unbraked towing capacity of 750 kg, powered by a 2.0L 4-cylinder diesel engine producing 154 kW and 500 Nm of torque. This capacity supports the transport of trailers, caravans, and equipment essential for remote exploration and industrial tasks[1].\n\nHigher-spec Ranger variants equipped with larger engines, including the 2.3L EcoBoost petrol and the 3.0L EcoBoost V6, offer towing capacities up to approximately 3,400 kg to 3,500 kg, with payloads generally around 1,000 kg, making them versatile for both heavy-duty work and recreational use[2][3][4].\n\nThe Ford Ranger Super Duty variant, developed specifically with Australian fleet and heavy-use customers in mind, markedly increases these capabilities. It features a Gross Vehicle Mass (GVM) and towing capacity both rated at 4,500 kg, with a Gross Combined Mass (GCM) of 8,000 kg. Payload capacities vary by cab configuration: single cab models can carry up to 1,982 kg, super cabs 1,885 kg, and double cabs 1,825 kg. These figures represent a substantial enhancement over standard Ranger models, enabling the Super Duty to carry heavier loads and tow larger trailers or machinery, which is critical for demanding environments like mining sites and large-scale agricultural operations[5].\n\nAdditional utility features of the Ranger Super Duty include a large 130-litre fuel tank for extended range, underbody protection with 5.0 mm thick steel plates rated for GVM loads, and a 400-watt inverter useful for powering tools and camping equipment. These adaptations underscore its design focus on ruggedness and practicality for Australian conditions[5].\n\nThe introduction of the Ranger plug-in hybrid (PHEV) model further diversifies the utility options. This variant combines a 2.3L turbocharged petrol engine with a 75 kW electric motor, delivering a combined 207 kW and 697 Nm of torque, with a payload capacity of 973 kg. This hybrid model balances utility with improved fuel efficiency and lower emissions, while maintaining sufficient payload for typical exploration and work demands[6].\n\nOverall, the towing and payload capacities across the Ford Ranger lineup, especially with the Super Duty and PHEV variants, provide Australian users with a range of options tailored to meet the rigorous demands of exploration, agriculture, mining, and other industries requiring reliable heavy-duty performance and versatility in diverse and challenging terrains.",
